ESA decides on major space missions: missions for billions
Far away planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to launch in the next few years.
Thirty proposals were available for selection, five are still in the race.
Far away worlds.
More than 1,000 planets have been found by astronomers around other stars.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: Should we look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origins of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and perhaps discover alien life?
These are the questions that the heads of the European Space Agency, ESA, are asking themselves.
For their programme Cosmic Vision, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that will make a decisive contribution to research.
The budget for such 'L-missions' is about one billion euros each.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
At the beginning of September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 ideas were up for debate, five of which have now been narrowed down.
Numerous bodies reviewed the proposals, checked with the researchers.
A final decision is expected to be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee in the next few days.
In total, ESA has selected four major questions for the missions of the Cosmic Vision programme, which was launched in 2007.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes that lead to the formation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus to the formation of planets orbiting these stars - are still in the dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has planets, what are the conditions under which life can arise?
To address this question, the Cheops space telescope is to be launched in 2017, to study in more detail the 500 known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity.
But the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres, searching for "biomarkers", gases that are considered indicators of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is ultimately intended to reveal the conditions for the origin of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation it emits with the planetary system play an important role.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied by example.
The European Space Agency has already approved an M-class mission (with a budget of about half a billion euros) for this purpose, the Solar Orbiter.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and will closely monitor the Sun's surface and activity.
Of great interest to researchers are also Jupiter and its moons.
They want to know what role this giant planet played in the evolution of the solar system.
The ESA is planning the first of three L-mission missions under the Cosmic Vision programme.
The Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer (JUICE) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to study the planet's atmosphere and the icy moons Europa, Callisto and Ganymede.
What are the fundamental physical laws of the universe?
The universe offers many opportunities to study matter in extreme conditions and to investigate whether the laws of nature we know still apply there.
Perhaps there are deviations that could lead physicists to a new theory that would unite all known laws of nature.
How did the universe come into existence and what is it made of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was born from the Big Bang.
In addition to the matter we see, which is made up of stars, planets and living beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters together, and dark energy, which speeds up the expansion of the universe.
Scientists still do not know what the laws of physics were during the first few seconds of the Big Bang, nor what dark matter and dark energy are.
With Euclid, ESA has already approved an M mission here, scheduled for launch in 2020.
Using a special telescope, the probe will study the distribution of matter in the universe across the entire sky for the first time, allowing conclusions to be drawn about the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection procedure.
The best chance of being approved as an L-mission is, according to many experts, "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand this as changes in the structure of space-time, predicted by Albert Einstein nearly 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could do it, the scientists behind the project hope.
The mission will include a two- or three-probe detector to be stationed in space.
Unlike facilities on Earth, it could also detect gravitational waves that were created in the Big Bang, providing new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called Athena, which will explore black holes, among other things; Icy Planets, another mission to the outer planets of the solar system; Prism, a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation; and Exoplanet Finder, which will track down and study Earth-like planets.
Proposals already outlined include the return of samples from Mars, the exploration of the Moon, Venus and asteroids, and solar physics.
