What happens to my email on the road?
E-mail is actually an electronic letter.
Was the design of the Internet service e-mail similar to that of the conventional postal service, and did it technically implement the letter of confidentiality?
The first Internet services were designed with the primary focus on enabling communication.
The basic technical protocols have therefore not been designed to provide a stable foundation for a sound exchange of letters.
A conventional e-mail is therefore more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
When user "Anna" sends an email to "Benni", are the computers of the two connected directly?
The first step is for Anna's email program or browser to send the mail to the mail server of her service provider.
If she has a Gmail account, for example, that would be Google.
This mail server sends the contents to the provider that Benni uses.
On the way, the mail can be run through several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content at his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read on their way through the net?
Most e-mails are read multiple times by software robots on the go.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail contains a malware as an attachment.
A virus check is also carried out on the receiving systems.
The providers also check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is deleted immediately or at least sorted into a spam folder.
Do the robots have any other tasks?
In systems such as Gmail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to place contextual advertising.
When Anna and Benni communicate via Gmail about their upcoming holiday, Google can display corresponding links to holiday offers.
Do people you don't know read your e-mails?
The likelihood of unauthorized persons reading an e-mail is extremely low.
But theoretically, it is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read e-mail.
The law also allows law enforcement agencies and intelligence services to intercept or read e-mails.
And that's not to mention the potential for illegal spying.
Is it possible to protect e-mails from being read?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With great technical effort, it is also possible to obscure the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even possible to identify who has communicated with whom.
