Why should an independent Scotland be expected to dance to the tune of Europe?
Why trade the London yoke for the Brussels one, especially now?
The real news in Europe is that the great post-war plan to unite Europe has been foiled.
The euro crisis has officially ended the European project.
Across the EU, parties hostile to the EU or seeking to discard the euro as the common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party, which was founded this year, was able to win almost five million votes in the September Bundestag elections, effectively ousting the Free Democrats (the British equivalent of the Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federal Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, is proving to be a turning point.
The strict austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, combined with the straitjacket imposed on the national economy by the common currency, has led many to believe that the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits  this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pegged its members to exchange rates that are favourable to German exporters  and German politicians would like to keep this up.
Without the possibility of devaluing the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage vis-√†-vis Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending  spurred on by Berlin.
The current budgetary and monetary problems are underpinned by a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the 'Green Energy Directives' enacted by Brussels, and a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers, European industry is paying twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the wage fixing in the world does not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into a corner by cheap American shale gas.
The result is a revolt, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and Europe has imposed its own economic policy, which the battered French economy has to contend with.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU National Front has just won a crucial by-election, pushing the ruling Socialists into third place.
The National Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the votes - a timely warning to the British Labour Party that it cannot assume that a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically mean advantages for the left.
