Mortgage companies boom in Singapore as the crisis hits the middle class
In a pawn shop in Singapore's Bendemeer Mall, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a gold bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay for her daughters' school fees.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, and I have put all my money in it", says Amirthalinga.
Although she earns S$3,000 (US$1,500) a month as an administrative assistant and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she says.
In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia - where household debt is rising - is so high that ValueMax, where it made its swap, became the third pawnbroker to be listed on the Singapore Exchange this week.
Securing jewelry is not only a quick way to get money  1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga , but it's also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, Singaporean mortgages charge an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank, a local lender with a branch in the same mall, charges.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no credit check or proof of income is required, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis, and cheap credit because of loose fiscal policies in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are looking to mortgage companies to make up the difference in a faltering economy.
This week, Standard & Poor's ratings agency called rising household debt, mainly from rising mortgages, a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
The Agency estimates that Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt to GDP ratio in Asia.
Malaysia tops the list with 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week barely emerged from a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed continued weakness in exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (of the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible", says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have further fueled the trend of selling off personal items as people take the opportunity to convert family jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items in the city-state's 200 pawn shops are gold.
People say, "The price of gold looks good, let's pawn Grandma's gold necklace and bring it back next month".
Thailand's largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen a 20 percent increase in customers at its branches in recent months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, which operates the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, is looking to expand not only into neighbouring Malaysia - where the company operates four properties - but also outside Asia, said ValueMax's chief executive, Yeah Lee Ching.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars it raised this week with its Singapore IPO.
While some lenders have been caught in the crossfire over high interest rates, Yeah explains that not only did pawn shops charge lower interest rates than other lenders, they also did not directly increase the debt.
'Customers borrow items they already own, and the liquidation of personal valuables does not increase the budget deficit', she explains.
The mortgage business is increasingly accepted by society as a short-term, secured financing.
Nor are all mortgage borrowers in financial difficulty.
Wealthy Singaporeans also come to ValueMax stores to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
We have clients from all walks of life.
These include wealthy people borrowing for a short-term business or investment, or small businesses that need to bridge cash-flow bottlenecks, says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
