Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play games, listen to music and watch movies from takeoff to landing, but not to use their cell phones, according to new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented would depend on the airline, FAA official Michael Huerta told a news conference.
Air carriers must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the flight crew training manuals and equipment fitting regulations to comply with the new regulations.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon", the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices when the doors of the aircraft are closed.
They can't be launched until the plane has reached an altitude of two miles and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the approach area, passengers must turn them off and must not restart them until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines that have electronically jammed aircraft could allow their passengers to use the devices during takeoff, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft retrofitted for use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Air Traffic Controllers Association, welcomed the changes.
If the new regulation is implemented safely and we are working closely with the airline on this , both sides will benefit from it, commented Glading.
We are frankly sorry to have to feel like we are the caretaker on this matter.
However, internet connections for surfing, exchanging emails, text messages or downloading data within three kilometres remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was publicly forced to leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the tarmac.
And heavier devices like laptops must still be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
The Commission has also proposed a number of amendments to the directive.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) has the authority to regulate telephone calls, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, the safety expert for national traffic issues, told CBS News that cell phones are still considered a risk.
"Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that airborne transmission can also interfere with broadcast masts", Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee, set up by the FAA to investigate this issue, recommended last month that the government allow for a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been increased pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on its use.
Critics, such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri, argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become pervasive.
Some studies have shown that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the switch.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966 after reports of interference with navigation and communication equipment by passenger-carried FM radios, then the latest technology.
New aircraft are far more reliant on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and FAA-approved to be immune to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi when they reach altitude for several years.
Airplanes adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less susceptible to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the increased use of electronic equipment under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, give off only minimal radiation when you flip through a page.
But when you download or send data, the transfer values are stronger.
Among those advocating a relaxation of restrictions on passenger device use is Amazon.com.
