Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risks of using the devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed the interference from the devices was real, even though the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there were only isolated reports of pilots claiming that the devices were interfering with aircraft systems, and most of these were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off the devices during instrument landings in poor visibility.
One travel industry grouping welcomed the changes, calling them a sensible adjustment for travelers who would be highly equipped with technology today.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not incompatible with safety", said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
