Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I'm reading a very sad book.
It's a book I thought would lift me up during my grim second year of medical school and give me hope again.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and it's about Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient notes and go to bed at night, this book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take the breath out of a speech.
The election was a landslide victory and news announcers paused to highlight the historic significance of this hour.
My classmates were crying with joy, and my parents were collecting all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on its way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had an approval rating of 82%.
And then I close the book.
To switch back to the present is a nasty awakening, like being ripped from a dream.
It is difficult to recall those optimistic times, but they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first voted, something has actually changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and diverse things that Obama has accomplished, from passing the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, ending the forced concealment of homosexuality in the military, and killing Osama bin Laden.
I too believe that the partisan blockade tactic has tipped the scales on many of the efforts that our nation should be moving forward with: immigration reform, a public option on health insurance, and the closing of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after countless times of defending the Obama administration to colleagues and acquaintances, I've come to the end of my attempts to explain.
I've reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows the wiretapping of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It can't explain why the National Security Agency collects data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are punished for exposing government misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a US citizen, was murdered without due process, nor why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the findings of a report which says that the White House's efforts to calm the media are the "most aggressive... since the Nixon administration".
And most recently, it can't excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the Affordable Care Act was passed.
I don't know if this is what I should have expected.
I wonder if I should have understood at 18 that government work could contradict the political campaigns that preceded it.
Obviously the MPs' office is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events like the Newtown massacre shape public debate.
But if I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely chosen by the government itself.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confusing and unrefined alternative, and he seemed unable to define his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had been hearing about for so long.
But with Obama's approval ratings dropping to below 45% this week, the return to 2008 has been made all the harder by this book.
It makes me long for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
