In contrast, the ratio in the United States is one doctor for every 413 persons.
But even if there were a doctor for them, most Cameroonians would not be able to afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of the country's health care spending is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty", Bwelle says.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
Seeing his father and so many of his countrymen suffer, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaound√©.
He also started a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people force themselves into minibuses and drive the medical equipment, strapped to the roof, across unpaved terrain to villages in need of help.
Things don't always go as smoothly as they should.
More than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are welcomed like heroes: a feast, song and dance and the finest accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebration and Bwelle  with his wide smile and boundless energy  is happy to join in the joyful celebration.
The next morning, the team begins examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip", said Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village  and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites, and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The operations are usually carried out in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recovery area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the O.R. and the disinfection equipment are fed by the group's generator, and so Bwelle and his volunteers work into the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a grueling process, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night long so we can stay awake and continue our work", says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team will head back to town, tired but proud of the work they've done.
The group - a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students - performed 700 free surgeries last year, and they know that their work makes a huge difference to the people they help.
One man explained that the free surgery he received for a hernia now enables him to return to work.
"This changes the future of my family", the man said.
In addition to his weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon at the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaound√©.
This second job finances 60% of his charity work, Bwelle said, with the rest coming from private donations.
"I really don't know when he sleeps", says Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers with Bwel's group.
He's always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe to support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain hands-on experience that they would never get back home.
"We can be present during surgeries, helping to draw blood or holding instruments for Dr. Bwelle", explains O'Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon and often bring donated sanitation.
But once they are in Yaound√©, Bwelle provides accommodation, transportation, and guidance.
"He is a hero, without a doubt", says O'Malley.
He has dedicated his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon knows no bounds.
Bwelle does not find the almost constant work a burden.
Helping others to live happier lives and thus fulfill a promise he made to his Father brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy doing this job", says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
Visit the ASCOVIME website to find out how you can help.
