Tourism: The Descent to the Romans
A Roman sewerage canal is preserved about 120 metres below Cologne.
If you're visiting Cologne, you can't miss the cathedral.
Its two towers rise to a height of some 157 meters, making it the second-tallest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two filigree towers of the cathedral realize that there is much to discover beneath the dome.
Rainer Schulze is an expert on the Cologne underworld.
The meeting point for his tours is the service centre of K√∂ln-Tourismus directly at the cathedral.
The tour starts in a very unspectacular way: "We start in the underground garage", says Schulze.
In the 1970s, the city fathers wanted a self-sustaining city, so only what was not too big remained of the remains of the old city wall.
Most users of the car park today therefore also rush past the Roman remains and only park their car.
But if you look closer, you will find an archaeological site in the parking deck D2, separated by metal bars.
The ruins are about 15 feet [5 m] high and made of hand-sized stones.
"These are remnants of the Roman city walls that were built in the second half of the first century A.D"., says Schulze.
Before the sun comes up again, Schulze lets the participants on the upper level of the park take a look inside a dark, 50-foot-deep shaft.
This is the old cathedral fountain, which is also hardly noticed.
The next stop on the tour is the Praetorium, where the participants descend back into the deep.
We are witnessing the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetor of the CCAA.
A visitor wants to know what CCAA means.
"The abbreviation stands for 'Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium,' which in good German means as much as 'City of Roman Law and City of the Agrippines, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the cult of the emperor.'"
And the Praetorium is the former governor's palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the exhibition hall, a tunnel leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here to a length of about 400 feet.
"You can walk along the Cloaca Maxima if you want", Schulze encourages the guests.
Schulze has a surprise.
After retrieving the key from the register, he leads the group to a 25-foot-deep, walkable shaft.
"We are now in the mikvah, a Jewish ritual bath", he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to access the groundwater that was essential for ritual washing.
To this day, the lower end of the Mikve, whose origins date back to the eighth century, is marked by varying water levels due to the changing level of the Rhine.
The mikvah will be part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, with construction due to begin shortly.
But it will take several years to complete.
