John Kerry makes an unprecedented admission that US spying has gone "unreasonably far"
John Kerry, in an unexpected admission, signaled a softening of the US's defensive stance towards its surveillance programs, saying that the spying had gone "unreasonably far" in certain cases.
The secretary of state also admitted that he shared with Barack Obama the responsibility for switching to "autopilot" when whistleblower Edward Snowden's explosive revelations about the NSA's spying activities became public.
The leak of information has thrown the US government into a diplomatic storm of indignation from its allies.
In a video address at the Open Government Conference in London, Kerry said: "Without question, the President and I and others in government have learned of some things that have gone off on what is essentially an autopilot, simply because the ability to do so existed, going back to World War II and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, 9/11".
He then became the first senior member of the US government to admit that the US spying had crossed a line, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said: "In some cases, the inappropriate has gone too far".
The president is determined to make things clear, and that's why he's conducting a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that there's been abuse.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons will not be impaired in this process.
But Kerry insisted that the NSA was a force for good and that its surveillance efforts had saved many lives.
He added: "We are dealing with a new world in which people are ready to blow themselves up".
There is a radical extremism in the world that is obsessed with killing people, blowing up things and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to catch it and stop it before it happens?
We have actually prevented plane crashes, attacks on buildings and the murder of people because we have known about such plans in advance.
Meanwhile, US lawmakers will travel to Europe to dispel concerns about alleged US spying and to convince Europeans of the need to continue to cooperate with the US in counterterrorism efforts, the chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy of Connecticut said he spoke to representatives of the European Parliament and others this week and was concerned about their threats to withdraw from anti-terrorist organizations due to frustration with the National Security Agency's surveillance.
"It is very important to the national security interests of the United States that Europeans stay on board with our joint efforts to fight terrorism", Murphy, a Democrat first elected to the Senate and chairman of the Senate's Foreign Relations and European Affairs Committee, said in an interview in Washington.
I'm also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, despite their anger at the NSA programs.
Media reports that the NSA has intercepted millions of phone records in Europe have strained relations with some US allies, though the head of the intelligence service this week said the reports were inaccurate and based on a misunderstanding of metadata collected by NATO allies and shared with the United States.
Other revelations cited documents leaked by Snowden that the NSA had monitored the mobile phone of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of national intelligence, James Clapper, defended the spying on allies as necessary, saying it was common on both sides.
In all the turmoil, Murphy said his office was preparing for the trip of the Congress to be held this year, and hoped the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other Members taking part will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact route is still being worked out.
While Murphy emphasised that the purpose of the trip was to improve relations, he also said that there would be some "serious words".
He said European governments must be honest with their people about the kind of spying programs they themselves have been using for years.
'While we can change our surveillance programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also come to terms with the fact that we are not the only ones spying,' said Murphy.
Meanwhile, John Kerry is scheduled to travel to the Middle East and Poland over the weekend to address the resentment over US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, and US surveillance activities.
