Australian woman appeals against Thailand jail sentence
A 21-year-old woman from Sydney, who was sentenced to 15 days in Phuket for falsely claiming to have been raped by a taxi driver, has appealed the verdict and has been released on bail.
Stevie Rochelle Bamford was initially found guilty by a Phuket provincial court on June 15 of making a false statement after she told the Thai police that a local taxi driver had raped her in the early hours of Sunday, June 10, while two other men were holding her.
However, later, video camera footage showed that she had safely reached her hotel after being separated from her Australian boyfriend.
The Phuket police questioned Bamford for two days before she confessed to making up the story.
Until the court hearing, she was in police custody at the scene.
Bamford was sentenced to 15 days in a low-security prison on the outskirts of Phuket, rather than an adult women's prison.
She is the daughter of Peter Tunks, a former Australian rugby league player who turned to the Foreign Office in Canberra for help for his daughter.
Tunks told the Sydney Sunday Telegraph that the whole family was "extremely concerned" about his daughter's well-being and wanted her back in Australia.
"We are of course very worried, but we hope that she will be back home as soon as possible", Tunks said.
Bamford has appealed the verdict and is free on bail of 50,000 baht.
Australian reports said she was vacationing in the resort town of Krabi in southern Thailand.
Outside the court, Bamford was represented by a local lawyer in Phuket and was warned that the appeal could also lead to a higher sentence of up to two years in an adult prison.
However, it is also possible that Thailand may be trying to improve its battered tourist image after the recent murder of tour operator Michelle Smith in Phuket, and therefore an acquittal is being sought.
